{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477191"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14224"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14224"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.09,0.09,0.31,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6911"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14224"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39623"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1730"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"3007"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"13217"},{"type":"tags","id":"13224"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with mild respiratory distress. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears mildly unwell. His pulse rate is 140/min, blood pressure 65/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He weighs 3 kg and has no obvious dysmorphic features. Cardiovascular examination reveals a loud, single second heart sound and a grade 3/6 systolic murmur best heard at the left sternal border. Chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly with increased pulmonary vascularity. Echocardiogram demonstrates truncus arteriosus. Blood tests reveal a serum calcium of 1.8 mmol/L (2.2-2.7).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Williams syndrome","Down syndrome","Foetal alcohol syndrome","Velocardiofacial syndrome","Noonan syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of a newborn with truncus arteriosus and hypocalcaemia strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Evelocardiofacial syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as 22q11.2 deletion syndrome or DiGeorge syndrome. This condition is characterised by a constellation of features, including congenital heart defects (particularly conotruncal anomalies like truncus arteriosus), hypocalcaemia due to hypoparathyroidism, and subtle facial dysmorphisms that may not be apparent in the neonatal period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilliams syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with cardiovascular abnormalities, particularly supravalvular aortic stenosis, and hypercalcaemia (not hypocalcaemia). The facial features (elfin facies) are usually recognisable, even in infancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDown syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with various congenital heart defects, most commonly atrioventricular septal defects. While it can cause hypocalcaemia, the combination with truncus arteriosus is less typical. Additionally, characteristic facial features are usually present at birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFoetal alcohol syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with growth deficiency, characteristic facial features (smooth philtrum, thin upper lip, small palpebral fissures), and central nervous system abnormalities. While it can cause congenital heart defects, the combination with hypocalcaemia is not typical, and there is no mention of maternal alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoonan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause congenital heart defects, most commonly pulmonary stenosis and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. However, truncus arteriosus is not a typical feature, and hypocalcaemia is not characteristic of this syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVelocardiofacial syndrome is the most likely diagnosis given the combination of truncus arteriosus and hypocalcaemia. The hypocalcaemia is due to underdevelopment of the parathyroid glands, which is a common feature of this syndrome. Early recognition is crucial for appropriate management of both the cardiac defect and the associated complications, including hypocalcaemia and immunodeficiency due to thymic hypoplasia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Velocardiofacial syndrome (22q11.2 deletion syndrome) is associated with congenital heart defects, particularly conotruncal anomalies like truncus arteriosus.","Hypocalcaemia is a common feature of velocardiofacial syndrome due to thymic and parathyroid gland abnormalities.","Early recognition of velocardiofacial syndrome is crucial for appropriate management of cardiac defects and associated complications."],"references":["McDonald-McGinn DM, Hain HS, Emanuel BS, et al. 22q11.2 Deletion Syndrome. 1999 Sep 23 [Updated 2024 May 9]. In: Adam MP, Feldman J, Mirzaa GM, et al., editors. GeneReviews\u00ae [Internet]. Seattle (WA): University of Washington, Seattle; 1993-2024. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1523/","Cort\u00e9s-Mart\u00edn J, Pe\u00f1uela NL, S\u00e1nchez-Garc\u00eda JC, Montiel-Troya M, D\u00edaz-Rodr\u00edguez L, Rodr\u00edguez-Blanque R. Deletion Syndrome 22q11.2: A Systematic Review. Children. 2022; 9(8):1168. Available at: https://doi.org/10.3390/children9081168"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39623"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14224"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39623"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-30T16:21:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-30T16:22:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6911"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54151"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Ge